<h2>Events in October 2018</h2>
<h3>Ex-hurricane Leslie</h3>
On 13 October 18 UTC hurricane Leslie transitioned into an extratropical cyclone, which three hours later made landfall in Portugal (Figure 1). Strong winds and heavy rain affected the entire country, leaving more than 300.000 homes without power and causing 2 deaths. Leslie was the strongest cyclone on the Iberian Peninsula since 1842. Although Leslie weakened while moving northeastward, on 15 October its interaction with a cold front over southwestern France lead to heavy rain and flash flooding causing large damage and 14 deaths.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/oct2018/AL1318large.png"><img alt="" src="../images/oct2018/AL1318large.png" width="300px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1. Ex-hurricane Leslie shortly before hitting Portugal - analysed weather map of 13 October 2018 18 UTC (Source: KNMI)</em>
<br><br>
<h3>Extreme weather in northern Italy</h3>
A deep low pressure system over northern Italy on 29 October caused strong wind and heavy precipitation (Figure 2). Millions of trees were uprooted, 9 people were killed, and Venice faced the worst flooding since at least 10 years. The pressure system induced a moist southerly flow from the warmer than normal Mediterranean, which when raised and blocked by the Alps lead to intense and prolonged precipitation.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/oct2018/ECMWF1.png"><img alt="" src="../images/oct2018/ECMWF1.png" width="300px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2. Surface pressure and precipitation over Europe on 29 October 2018 18 UTC, with a low pressure system and heavy precipitation over northern Italy (Source: ECMWF/KNMI).</em>
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for October 2018</h2>
In most of Europe the number of cold days was lower than in the reference period 1981-2010 (Figure 3). As 'cold' relates to the lowest 10 percentile range, the reference number of cold days is about 3. In western Europe and Scandinavia the number of cold days relative to the 30-years average were lower than normal in this period.
